regression model:

the first objective for the exercise was to build the regression model between sentiments/emotion and retweets/favourites. to do this i decided to recode the two variables (negative and positive) to create a single one called “sentiments”. to do this i decided to make it positive - negative. the variable then has a scale from 10 to -6, where the two extremes are very positive(10) and very negative(-6)

ggplot(trump_tweets2, aes(x = retweet_count , y = sentiments)) +
  scale_y_binned() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", col = "red") +
  ylab("Average Sentiment") +
  xlab("Number of retweet") +
  ggtitle("Regression model among Sentiment and Retweets")+
  theme_bw()

ggplot(trump_tweets2, aes(x = favorite_count , y = sentiments)) +
  scale_y_binned() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", col = "green") +
  ylab("Average Sentiment") +
  xlab("Number of Favorites") +
  ggtitle("Regression model among Sentiment and Favorites")+
  theme_bw()

the two graphs above show the regression between the sentiments variable and the number of retweets and favourites. both models show a negative relationship, although for retweets the slope is greater. this means that sentiments tend to be more negative when the number of interactions to the tweet increases

grouping emotion:

# create a variable for negative emotions with the function add_column and %>% operator
trump_tweets2 <- trump_tweets2 %>% 
  add_column(
  neg_emotions= (trump_tweets2$sadness) + 
    (trump_tweets2$anger) + 
    (trump_tweets2$disgust) + 
    (trump_tweets2$fear)
  )
# create a variable for positive emotions with the function add_column and %>% operator
trump_tweets2 <- trump_tweets2 %>% 
  add_column(
    pos_emotions= (trump_tweets2$joy) + 
      (trump_tweets2$anticipation) + 
      (trump_tweets2$surprise) + 
      (trump_tweets2$trust)
  )
# create a variable for emotions with the function add_column and %>% operator. i set up the function
# doing positive emotions - negative emotions
trump_tweets2 <- trump_tweets2 %>% 
  add_column(
    emotions= (trump_tweets2$pos_emotions) - (trump_tweets2$neg_emotions) 
)

##create a ratio for sentiments and emotions
# in order to weight the number of total words, i divided the function emotions and sentiments for the variable tot_words.

trump_tweets2 <- trump_tweets2 %>% 
  add_column(
    sentimentsratio= (trump_tweets2$sentiments)/(trump_tweets2$tot_words))
 
trump_tweets2 <- trump_tweets2 %>% 
  add_column(
    emotionsratio= ((trump_tweets2$pos_emotions)-(trump_tweets2$neg_emotions))/(trump_tweets2$tot_words)
)

with regard to the emotion variables (anger, anticipation, joy, disgust, sadness, fear, surprise and trust) I decided to recode them in a similar way to that used for sentiments: I divided them into two groups, one positive (anticipation, joy, trust and surprise) the other negative (disgust, fear, sadness, anger) and subtracted them. the emotion variable is a scale ranging from 21 (very positive emotions) to -14 (very negative emotions)

ggplot(trump_tweets2, aes(x = favorite_count , y = emotions)) +

TASK 4

Step 4 of the exercise finally asks you to analyse the number of tweets written from trump’s profile. this involves analysing 4 main dates:

  • June 16, 2015 (Trump campaign was officially launched) blue line

  • May 4, 2016 (Trump became the presumptive nominee for the Republicans) green line

  • July 19, 2016 (Trump became the the official nominee) yellow line

  • November 8, 2016 (The presidential elections happened) red line

In order to evidence in the graphs those dates, i decide to use the function geom_vline, setting the first tweet number of the day. In order to have a clearer view of these periods, I decided to set up the graphs starting on 01-01-2015.

# using as.numeric function to set the position of the first tweet for a selected day
ggplot(trump_tweets2, aes(x=date)) + 
  geom_freqpoly(stat = "count")+   
  geom_vline(xintercept=as.numeric(trump_tweets2$date[22157]),lwd=0.75,colour="blue")+
  geom_vline(xintercept=as.numeric(trump_tweets2$date[27712]),lwd=0.75,colour="green")+
  geom_vline(xintercept=as.numeric(trump_tweets2$date[28492]),lwd=0.75,colour="yellow")+
  geom_vline(xintercept=as.numeric(trump_tweets2$date[29945]),lwd=0.75,colour="red")+
  scale_x_date(limits = as.Date(c("2015-01-01","2017-03-25")))+   #to focus only from 2015 to 2017
  labs(y= "number of tweets", x = "date")

the first graph here above relates the number of tweets for each day. as we can clearly see the largest number of tweets is written in the first period before his official candidacy, reaching a peak of about 150 tweets in early 2015. in the second period between the blue and green lines (campaign and presumptive nominee for the Republicans) the number of tweets seems fairly constant, except for a short period towards the end of 2015, when there is a peak of about 80 tweets per day. the same situation between the green and yellow lines (Trump became the official nominee for Republican party). in that period there is a lower peak of almost 50 tweets per day. the most interesting period seems to me to be the period before the elections: in this period of time we can see how the number of tweets increases progressively, reaching almost 100tweets/day. it would be interesting to see the source of the tweets, because most probably these tweets were written by political professionals, thus by trump’s staff. finally, the last period (after the presidential election in which trump won) we can see that the total number of tweets is very low and constant.

EXERCISE 2- SPOTIFY

#open packages and import dataset
library(rio)
setwd("/Users/trava/Downloads/")
spotify <- import("spotify.rds")

library(tidyverse)
library(dplyr)
options(scipen = 999)

in this latest exercise regarding the spotify dataset, I decided to consider these three artists:

  • U2
  • Good Charlotte
  • PRhyme

I then created a dataset with these three artists by averaging the features for each, using the summarise_at function. this dataframe is called mean_my the purpose is to see the averages of each feature by comparing them to all the others within the dataset. i also created another dataframe with the mean of features for all the observations, that i called mean_spotify the last step in creating the dataset was to merge the two datasets using the rbind function. the dataframe used will be this merged one, which i called totalmean: the observations are: u2, good charlotte, prhyme and total.

#creating a dataset called df with only the observation for u2, good charlotte and prhyme

df <- spotify %>% 
  filter(artist_name == "U2"|
           artist_name =="Good Charlotte"| 
           artist_name =="PRhyme")

# calculating mean for features i select with the function summarise_at
mean_my <- df %>% 
  group_by(artist_name) %>% 
  summarise_at(vars("acousticness","danceability", "duration_ms", "energy", "instrumentalness",
                    "key", "liveness", "loudness", "mode", "speechiness", "tempo",
                    "time_signature",  "valence", "popularity"),mean)
#calculating the mean for features i select from the principal dataset. i didnt set the function group_by, in order to 
#calculate the sample mean
mean_spotify <- spotify %>% 
  summarise_at(vars("acousticness","danceability", "duration_ms", "energy", "instrumentalness",
                    "key", "liveness", "loudness", "mode", "speechiness", "tempo",
                    "time_signature",  "valence", "popularity"),mean)
#creating a dataframe with the sample mean, adding also a new column with artist name=total.
#i need to do that because its crucial for merging the two dataframe(number of columns must be the same)
mean_spotify <- mean_spotify %>% 
  add_column(artist_name = "total")
#merging the two dataframe
totalmean <- rbind(mean_my, mean_spotify)
table(totalmean$artist_name)
## 
## Good Charlotte         PRhyme          total             U2 
##              1              1              1              1

1- Acousticness

This value describes how acoustic a song is. A score of 1.0 means the song is most likely to be an acoustic one.

ggplot(data= totalmean, aes(y = acousticness, x = reorder(artist_name, acousticness, function(x) mean(x, na.rm = T)),)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_text(aes(label = artist_name), nudge_y = -0.01)+
  geom_text(aes(label = round(acousticness,digits = 2)), nudge_y = 0.015)+
  xlab("Artist") +
  ylab("Acousticness") +
  theme_bw()

this graph show that i probably prefer music with less instruments. the difference between total and, for example, Good charlotte is very noticeable.

2- Danceability

“Danceability describes how suitable a track is for dancing based on a combination of musical elements including tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity. A value of 0.0 is least danceable and 1.0 is most danceable”.

8- Popularity

ggplot(data= totalmean, aes(y = popularity, x = reorder(artist_name, popularity, function(x) mean(x, na.rm = T)),)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_text(aes(label = artist_name), nudge_y = -0.01)+
  geom_text(aes(label = round(popularity,digits = 2)), nudge_y = 0.015)+
  xlab("Artist") +
  ylab("Popularity") +
  theme_bw()

the last graph concerns the average popularity of the artists’ songs. the scale goes from 0 to 100, where 100 is the maximum popularity value. as shown, two of my top three artists are above the sample mean, while only prhyme is below this value.
